01:21:23.280 --> 01:21:24.580
&gt;&gt; Dr. Dr. Mark Dickens: Okay.

01:21:24.580 --> 01:21:25.880
So just briefly, the
-- pretty much all

01:21:25.880 --> 01:21:28.490
of the Iranian scripts were based

01:21:28.490 --> 01:21:31.960
on the Aramaic alphabet
before Syriac had developed

01:21:31.960 --> 01:21:33.270
as a separate alphabet.

01:21:33.270 --> 01:21:38.330
So Pahlavi, Sogdian,
from Sogdian came Uighur.

01:21:38.330 --> 01:21:40.720
From Uigher came Mongolian script.

01:21:40.720 --> 01:21:49.800
Hotanese was actually often written
in the Brahmi script from India.

01:21:49.800 --> 01:21:55.330
But as far as the Syriac script
that was carried eastward,

01:21:55.330 --> 01:22:01.560
the languages that were
used to -- the Christian --

01:22:01.560 --> 01:22:03.020
to produce Christian material

01:22:03.020 --> 01:22:06.350
in using the Syriac
script were Sogdian.

01:22:06.350 --> 01:22:09.720
So Sogdian was -- Sogdian
Christian material is found both

01:22:09.720 --> 01:22:13.090
in the Sogdian script, the native
Sogdian script that comes directly

01:22:13.090 --> 01:22:16.260
from Aramaic, and in
the Syriac script,

01:22:16.260 --> 01:22:21.060
and also Turkic material is
found both in the Uighur script,

01:22:21.060 --> 01:22:23.720
which is dependent on the
Sogdian script, which is dependent

01:22:23.720 --> 01:22:26.540
on Aramaic, and in
the Syriac script.

01:22:26.540 --> 01:22:30.190
And there are a couple of
fragments in New Persian,

01:22:30.190 --> 01:22:32.990
which are also written
in the Syriac script.

01:22:32.990 --> 01:22:36.650
But the only Middle
Persian material we have is

01:22:36.650 --> 01:22:39.390
that Saltar [assumed spelling], and
it's only in the Pahlavi script.

